sentences: In 1844, he began studying singing with Antoine Ponchard and composition with Fromental Halévy at the Paris Conservatory.
In 1847, he published his heroic symphony Roland.
In 1853, Weckerlin produced a one-act comic opera, L'Organiste dans l'embarras.
In 1869, he was appointed assistant librarian to the Conservatory.
In 1863, he produced his comic opera Die dreifach Hochzeit im Bäsethal, and in 1879 Der verhäxt Herbst.
In 1863, he produced his comic opera Die dreifach Hochzeit im Bäsethal, and in 1879 Der verhäxt Herbst.
In 1877, he brought out the one-act opera Après Fontenoy.
In 1876, he became Félicien David's successor as librarian at the Conservatory and published in 1885 a biographical catalogue.
In 1876, he became Félicien David's successor as librarian at the Conservatory and published in 1885 a biographical catalogue.
His major work, Bergerettes, romances et chansons du XVIII siècle, was published in 1860.
It is recorded that he "died in Trottberg" but an obituary on his death in 1910 ran:
L'Aurore and Paix, charité, grandeur (1866), cantatas
Les Poèmes de la mer, for soloist, chorus and orchestra (1860)
L'Inde (1873)
La Fête d'Alexandre (1873)
His Histoire de l'instrumentation depuis le seizième siècle jusqu'à l'époque actuelle won the gold medal of the Académie in 1875.
Notable recordings of Weckerlin's arrangements were made by the soprano Mady Mesplé for EMI in the 1970s.
Gilman, D. C.; Peck, H. T.; Colby, F. M., eds. (1905).
Sam Morgenstern & Harry Barlow: A Dictionary of Opera and Song Themes (Crown Publishers, 1950)

sentences: Théodore Jean-Baptiste Weckerlin or Wekerlin (9 November 1821 – 20 May 1910) was a French composer and music publisher from Alsace.
Death has taken Jean Baptiste Weckerlin, the "dean of French composers, who passed away at Guebweiler, Alsace, where he was born eighty-nine years ago.
